column5: Average Fiscal capital income [total fiscal income ranking] within a given percentile group. Fiscal capital income  is income received by virtue of owning capital.  Reported on income tax returns before any specific deduction. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the individual (rather than the household). This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.
column6: Average Dividends within a given percentile group. Dividends are payments from corporations to shareholders, usually as a distribution of profits.  Reported on income tax returns before any specific deduction. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the individual (rather than the household). This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.
column7: Average Fiscal income within a given percentile group. Fiscal income is defined as the sum of all income items reported on income tax returns, before any deduction. It includes labour income, capital income and mixed income. The concept of fiscal income varies with national tax legislations, so in order to make international comparisons it is preferable to use the concept of national income. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the individual (rather than the household). This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.
column8: Average Fiscal income within a given percentile group. Fiscal income is defined as the sum of all income items reported on income tax returns, before any deduction. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the tax unit defined by national fiscal administrations to measure personal income taxes.
column9: Average Interest within a given percentile group. Interest is payments from borrowers to lenders above repayments of the principal sum. column10: Average Fiscal labour income [total fiscal income ranking] within a given percentile group. Fiscal labour income  is wages and pensions as a remuneration in exchange for labour. This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.
column11: Average Capital component of mixed income within a given percentile group. Capital component of mixed income is net mixed income that is derived from providing capital as a factor of production. Net mixed income is defined as the surplus or deficit accruing from production by unincorporated enterprises owned by households (sometimes termed as "business income").  Reported on income tax returns before any specific deduction. Reported on income tax returns before any specific deduction. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. column50: Average Pre-tax national income within a given percentile group. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column62: Total Personal equity, fund shares & offshore wealth within a given percentile group. Personal equity, fund shares & offshore wealth are company stocks, fund shares and wealth outside of one's residence country owned by the personal sector (households).. The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column63: Total Personal financial assets excluding currency & deposits within a given percentile group. Personal financial assets excluding cash are financial assets except cash and bank deposits owned by the personal sector (households).. The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column64: Total Personal financial assets within a given percentile group. Personal financial assets include bank deposits, bonds, stocks and other financial claims held by households.. The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column65: Total Personal currency, bonds & deposits within a given percentile group. Personal currency, deposits, bonds & loans are cash, bank deposits, bonds and loans held by households.. The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column66: Total Personal housing assets within a given percentile group. Personal housing assets are dwellings (including land underlying dwellings) held by households.. The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column67: Total Personal land underlying dwellings within a given percentile group. Personal land underlying dwellings is land on which the places of residence held by households are built. . The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column68: Total Personal natural capital within a given percentile group. Personal natural capital corresponds to natural assets (minerals, energy and other environmental resources excluding agricultural land) owned by the personal sector (households).. The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column69: Total Personal non-financial assets within a given percentile group. Personal non-financial assets include housing, land and all other domestic material and immaterial assets (machinery, equipment, patents, etc.) held directly by households, as opposed to non-financial assets owned indirectly through financial assets (equities, bonds, etc. in corporations holding non-financial assets). . The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column70: Total Personal other domestic capital within a given percentile group. Other domestic personal capital includes all non-financial assets held by households and foundations, except housing assets and agricultural land: machinery, equipment, patents, etc. . The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column71: Total Personal pension funds & life insurance within a given percentile group. Personal pension funds & life insurance are pension funds and life insurance owned by the personal sector (households).. The personal or household sector - in the national accounts sense - includes all households and private individuals (including those living in institutions), as well as unincorporated enterprises whose accounts are not separated from those of the households who own them. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column72: Total Pre-tax national income  within a given percentile group. Pre-tax national income  is the sum of all pre-tax personal income flows accruing to the owners of the production factors, labor and capital, before taking into account the operation of the tax/transfer system, but after taking into account the operation of pension system. The central difference between personal factor income and pre-tax income is the treatment of pensions, which are counted on a contribution basis by factor income and on a distribution basis by pre-tax income. The population is comprised of individuals of all ages.
column73: Fiscal income share held by a given percentile group. Fiscal income is defined as the sum of all income items reported on income tax returns, before any deduction. It includes labour income, capital income and mixed income. The concept of fiscal income varies with national tax legislations, so in order to make international comparisons it is preferable to use the concept of national income. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the individual (rather than the household). This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.
column74: Pre-tax national income share held by a given percentile group. Pre-tax national income  is the sum of all pre-tax personal income flows accruing to the owners of the production factors, labor and capital, before taking into account the operation of the tax/transfer system, but after taking into account the operation of pension system. The central difference between personal factor income and pre-tax income is the treatment of pensions, which are counted on a contribution basis by factor income and on a distribution basis by pre-tax income. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the individual (rather than the household). This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.
column75: Fiscal income threshold value at a given percentile.  Fiscal income is defined as the sum of all income items reported on income tax returns, before any deduction. It includes labour income, capital income and mixed income. The concept of fiscal income varies with national tax legislations, so in order to make international comparisons it is preferable to use the concept of national income. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the individual (rather than the household). This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.
column76: Pre-tax national income threshold value at a given percentile.  Pre-tax national income  is the sum of all pre-tax personal income flows accruing to the owners of the production factors, labor and capital, before taking into account the operation of the tax/transfer system, but after taking into account the operation of pension system. The central difference between personal factor income and pre-tax income is the treatment of pensions, which are counted on a contribution basis by factor income and on a distribution basis by pre-tax income. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the individual (rather than the household). This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.
